content.html:
The 12 Labours Portal has extended the knowledge framework developed by the Physiome system and has enabled users to create personalised Physiome models that link to clinical practice and home healthcare.

The portal brings international physiological research into multiscale whole body models, allowing you to run computational models from cells, to functional tissue units, to organs.

The overall goal for the 12 Labours project is to further develop the predictive modelling capability that we and our international partners have built in the Physiome Project, and to add personalised modelling to assist in the clinical diagnosis and treatment of a range of medical conditions.


We are building tools which allow us to better understand, diagnose and treat the human body. Cell by cell, organ by organ we are developing a model of the human body. Our vision is to have this model available for anyone who wants one as part of their medical record. Data from a wide range of sources including health records, medical equipment and wearable sensors will be combined to personalise this model to be a digital twin. With this digital twin we will be better able to monitor, treat and even predict our health into the future.


Advances in technology and medicine have vastly improved our ability to diagnose and treat medical conditions. Medical imaging and diagnosis equipment allows us to look within the body and see how it works. We can use this data to build models of  individual cells, organs and even organ systems to increase our understanding of how they work and how disease can impact their function. The Auckland Bioengineering Institute has been at the forefront of biomedical modelling for over two decades. With the 12 Labours project we are using this modelling experience to develop a digital twin. We have identified three core areas required to develop digital twins and give the broadest use and impact.      

  1. Building more accurate models that incorporate multiple scales from cells and tissue units through to organs, and combining these organ models to build organ systems and complete digital twins.

  2. Building interoperability, standardisation and security into our predictive modelling frameworks to allow models and data to be secure, personalised and reusable.

  3. Increasing the sources of data available to us and the frequency at which we get data through developing and using data from wearables, implantables and point-of-care devices.

contents.html: A framework for personalised Physiome modelling. This allows users to combine models, link models across spatial and temporal scales, and to personalise the models.
A Physiome modelling platform for precision medicine. This allows medical professionals to implement personalised Physiome models in a clinical setting.

Continuous monitoring using workflows that will allow personalised Physiome models that can connect to wearable, implanted and home-based devices. This allows a continuous flow of data to update an individual’s personalised model for diagnostic monitoring and predicting therapeutic outcomes.

The 12 Labours project is built around a number of international partnerships including:

  • cardio-respiratory applications (University of Freiburg, University of Oxford),
  • rehabilitation of upper limb mechanics (University of Stuttgart, Stanford University),
  • smooth muscle mechanics (Technische Universitat Braunschweig), 
  • reproductive sciences (Newcastle, Warwick University, Eindhoven University of Technology), 
  • uterine anatomy (Ludwig-Maximilians-Universitat).

The project also participates International Research Training Programmes with:

  • University of Stuttgart, 
  • Fraunhofer Institute for Manufacturing Engineering and Automation IPA
  • University of Freiburg and, 
  • Sheffield University

content.html:
12 Labours aims to improve understanding and diagnosis of medical conditions by bringing physiological models and the predictions made by these models into standard clinical practice. 

Deeper understanding of the human body and physiology has improved medical treatment and health outcomes. We want to take understanding, treatment and ultimately prediction of medical conditions as far as possible through developing computational physiological models. This is driving us to develop accurate models that encompass all scales of physiology from the cell to organ and body as a system. 

Modeles are driven by data. We will increase the sources and frequency of data available to use though using existing medical data, incorporating data from wearables, implantables and home based monitoring equipment and developing new instrumentation and devices to give access to new types of physiological data. 

The complexity of linking models over multiple scales and organs requires us to ensure we standardise the models and ensure they are interoperable.  The same is true for the data used to create these models which has to be stored in a standardised and secure way. This will allow our data and models to be combined as required and run in a unified framework.
The 12 Labours project works on grants and donations. If you would like to support the 12 Labours project then you can donate today!

The 12 Labours project promotes open scientific research through its mission to provide freely available online data, software and other resources relating to physiome modelling.

Our Terms of Service are designed to explain how you can use our portal, websites and applications.
